WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.935 --> 00:00:04.769
Every story has a beginning.

2
00:00:04.838 --> 00:00:08.640
But ours doesn't start
the way you might think.

3
00:00:08.709 --> 00:00:11.976
<i>Sure. it begins on a
street that looks like most.</i>

4
00:00:12.045 --> 00:00:15.047
<i>And with a family that was.
for the most part. normal.</i>

5
00:00:15.116 --> 00:00:16.116
<i>Average.</i>

6
00:00:16.183 --> 00:00:17.815
<i>Ordinary.</i>

7
00:00:17.884 --> 00:00:19.629
<i>It was the morning I
convinced my wife. Stephanie.</i>

8
00:00:19.653 --> 00:00:23.022
<i>to turn her research trip into a
much needed family vacation.</i>

9
00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:26.269
While your mom's working we'll
be out and about exploring Belem.

10
00:00:26.293 --> 00:00:27.404
Belem?

11
00:00:27.428 --> 00:00:28.727
It's in Brazil. sweetie.

12
00:00:28.795 --> 00:00:29.795
Brazil?

13
00:00:29.863 --> 00:00:30.940
South America. dumb ass.

14
00:00:30.964 --> 00:00:32.064
Hey. hey.

15
00:00:32.132 --> 00:00:33.276
I just don't know why
we have to go right now.

16
00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:34.966
It's not a good time
for me and Lucas.

17
00:00:35.035 --> 00:00:36.480
Not a good time? You've only
been dating this kid for two weeks!

18
00:00:36.504 --> 00:00:38.315
When did you start
dating Lucas Fisher?

19
00:00:38.339 --> 00:00:39.583
Just because you Twitter-spy me.

20
00:00:39.607 --> 00:00:41.250
doesn't mean that you
know everything about my life.

21
00:00:41.274 --> 00:00:43.875
When was the last time we did
something together as a family?

22
00:00:43.944 --> 00:00:45.488
Last month. You forced
us to play charades

23
00:00:45.512 --> 00:00:48.591
and then you pulled out your back
miming some scene from <i>Iron Man.</i>

24
00:00:48.615 --> 00:00:51.549
That was an old sports
injury I re-aggravated.

25
00:00:51.618 --> 00:00:54.898
No. I mean when was the last
time we did something as a family?

26
00:00:56.523 --> 00:00:58.289
Yellowstone. three years ago.

27
00:00:58.358 --> 00:00:59.658
We all got poison ivy.

28
00:00:59.726 --> 00:01:01.593
There's no poison
ivy in Brazil. kid.

29
00:01:01.662 --> 00:01:03.028
Right?

30
00:01:03.097 --> 00:01:04.674
I just don't know why you
guys can't go without me

31
00:01:04.698 --> 00:01:06.343
and then photoshop me in later.

32
00:01:06.367 --> 00:01:08.734
Look. we're all gonna go.

33
00:01:08.803 --> 00:01:12.163
and we're all gonna
have the time of our lives.

34
00:01:15.609 --> 00:01:18.009
DAPHNE: That's the
plane? Are you kidding?

35
00:01:18.078 --> 00:01:19.189
STEPHANIE: It
does look a little...

36
00:01:19.213 --> 00:01:20.712
Like a flying coffin.

37
00:01:20.781 --> 00:01:22.848
JIM: Come on. you guys.
Since we've been here.

38
00:01:22.917 --> 00:01:24.360
we have not done
one thing together.

39
00:01:24.384 --> 00:01:27.730
You text. You work. And
you stare at the television.

40
00:01:27.754 --> 00:01:29.399
You gotta concentrate.
It's in South American.

41
00:01:29.423 --> 00:01:31.223
For one hour.

42
00:01:31.292 --> 00:01:34.538
we are going to take a
sunset tour of the rainforest.

43
00:01:34.562 --> 00:01:35.894
Together. as a family.

44
00:01:35.963 --> 00:01:37.962
Because that's how
memories are made.

45
00:01:38.031 --> 00:01:40.799
Whether you want them or not!

46
00:01:40.868 --> 00:01:42.467
(THUNDER CRASHING)

47
00:01:50.777 --> 00:01:53.423
Hey. this storm really
came out of nowhere. huh?

48
00:01:53.447 --> 00:01:54.746
Don't worry.

49
00:01:54.815 --> 00:01:56.259
I've flown through much worse.

50
00:01:56.283 --> 00:01:58.183
Yeah? When?

51
00:01:58.252 --> 00:02:00.396
Actually. I was just trying
to make you feel better.

52
00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:02.740
This is about as bad
as I've ever been up in.

53
00:02:04.758 --> 00:02:06.158
Who are you texting now?

54
00:02:06.227 --> 00:02:07.227
God.

55
00:02:08.362 --> 00:02:09.394
(DAPHNE SHRIEKS)

56
00:02:09.462 --> 00:02:11.502
Where are your life
vests? Back there.

57
00:02:11.998 --> 00:02:13.031
Hold on.

58
00:02:13.100 --> 00:02:15.140
Dad? It's okay. pussy cat.

59
00:02:15.235 --> 00:02:16.312
Are we gonna crash?

60
00:02:16.336 --> 00:02:17.402
JIM: Here.

61
00:02:18.338 --> 00:02:19.338
Okay. kid.

62
00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:22.273
It's just like Space
Mountain. right?

63
00:02:22.342 --> 00:02:24.253
As soon as Mitch gets
us down safe and sound.

64
00:02:24.277 --> 00:02:26.845
you'll be begging me to
go up again. I promise.

65
00:02:26.914 --> 00:02:28.179
(LIGHTNING STRIKES)

66
00:02:29.349 --> 00:02:31.327
That didn't happen
on Space Mountain.

67
00:02:31.351 --> 00:02:33.018
PILOT: Mayday. mayday. mayday.

68
00:02:33.086 --> 00:02:35.453
This is Papa. Delta.
Baker. Alpha. Sierra.

69
00:02:35.522 --> 00:02:37.334
We've got complete
engine failure.

70
00:02:37.358 --> 00:02:39.324
I'm gonna die. And I
haven't even done it yet.

71
00:02:41.695 --> 00:02:42.895
Listen. listen.

72
00:02:42.963 --> 00:02:44.762
We're gonna be
all right. I promise.

73
00:02:44.831 --> 00:02:46.511
Have I ever lied to you before?

74
00:02:48.001 --> 00:02:49.601
About anything this important?

75
00:02:49.669 --> 00:02:51.136
Yeah.

76
00:02:51.204 --> 00:02:52.771
(THUNDER CRASHING)

77
00:02:52.839 --> 00:02:53.872
Buckle up!

78
00:03:03.517 --> 00:03:04.616
Steph!

79
00:03:05.352 --> 00:03:07.152
Me. too.

80
00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:10.620
JIM: <i>At that moment I couldn't help
wondering how my family got here.</i>

81
00:03:11.325 --> 00:03:12.957
<i>from here.</i>

82
00:03:13.026 --> 00:03:15.227
<i>A time that was quite simply...</i>

83
00:03:15.296 --> 00:03:17.262
<i>perfect.</i>

84
00:03:17.331 --> 00:03:19.331
And I had never been happier.

85
00:03:20.234 --> 00:03:22.011
<i>But if there is a downside</i>

86
00:03:22.035 --> 00:03:25.136
<i>to your family being the
center of your entire world...</i>

87
00:03:25.205 --> 00:03:26.705
Toss the rock with Dad?

88
00:03:26.774 --> 00:03:29.151
<i>It's that eventually
all families grow up.</i>

89
00:03:29.175 --> 00:03:30.453
Wanna play some ball with Daddy?

90
00:03:30.477 --> 00:03:32.143
<i>Grow apart.</i>

91
00:03:32.212 --> 00:03:34.580
<i>Stephanie barely
had time to notice.</i>

92
00:03:34.648 --> 00:03:36.314
<i>Who could blame her?</i>

93
00:03:36.383 --> 00:03:39.028
<i>Her career as a research
scientist had taken off.</i>

94
00:03:39.052 --> 00:03:41.720
Executive Vice
President of Research.

95
00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:45.056
<i>And I was happy for her.</i>

96
00:03:49.730 --> 00:03:51.496
<i>But I missed...</i>

97
00:03:51.564 --> 00:03:53.265
<i>us.</i>

98
00:03:53.333 --> 00:03:55.867
<i>We were all living
under the same roof.</i>

99
00:03:55.936 --> 00:03:58.670
<i>but in different worlds.</i>

100
00:03:58.738 --> 00:04:00.572
<i>And I was all alone in mine.</i>

101
00:04:02.776 --> 00:04:04.843
<i>So that's how we got here.</i>

102
00:04:04.911 --> 00:04:06.378
<i>And this.</i>

103
00:04:06.446 --> 00:04:07.845
<i>this was the beginning.</i>

104
00:04:13.753 --> 00:04:15.153
Hold on!

105
00:04:15.222 --> 00:04:16.988
JJ: Oh. my God!

106
00:04:17.057 --> 00:04:18.590
PILOT: Brace for impact!

107
00:04:21.695 --> 00:04:22.928
Hold on!

108
00:04:34.675 --> 00:04:35.675
JJ: Dad!

109
00:04:36.477 --> 00:04:37.676
Mom!

110
00:04:37.744 --> 00:04:39.222
JIM: <i>Fortunately.
we all survived.</i>

111
00:04:39.246 --> 00:04:40.279
Jim. the pilot.

112
00:04:40.347 --> 00:04:42.013
Mitch!

113
00:04:42.082 --> 00:04:44.349
<i>Unfortunately. our
pilot wasn't as lucky.</i>

114
00:04:44.418 --> 00:04:46.284
Get up. JJ!

115
00:04:46.353 --> 00:04:47.953
<i>We held each other close.</i>

116
00:04:51.058 --> 00:04:53.225
<i>vowing a new
beginning to things.</i>

117
00:04:54.261 --> 00:04:55.961
<i>Sincere.</i>

118
00:04:56.029 --> 00:04:57.462
<i>heartfelt promises.</i>

119
00:05:03.637 --> 00:05:05.081
Yes. all right. well.
just shoot me an email

120
00:05:05.105 --> 00:05:06.916
and I will see you first
thing in the morning.

121
00:05:06.940 --> 00:05:07.973
All right. bye.

122
00:05:09.309 --> 00:05:11.409
JJ. remember. your
report's due tomorrow.

123
00:05:11.478 --> 00:05:13.256
And Daphne. you need to
find your basketball uniform.

124
00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:14.545
DAPHNE: Yeah. fine.

125
00:05:14.614 --> 00:05:15.880
Sorry.

126
00:05:15.949 --> 00:05:17.048
(SIGHS)

127
00:05:17.117 --> 00:05:19.050
That was Katie from the lab.

128
00:05:20.253 --> 00:05:21.720
You okay?

129
00:05:21.788 --> 00:05:27.225
Guess it was crazy to think
a trip would change anything.

130
00:05:27.294 --> 00:05:30.929
Look. Jim. I know you wanted us
to have some great family moments.

131
00:05:30.997 --> 00:05:33.231
but. come on. we survived
a plane crash together.

132
00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:35.400
Talk about a memory
that'll last a lifetime.

133
00:05:35.468 --> 00:05:36.667
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

134
00:05:39.473 --> 00:05:41.272
Yeah. it's work. it can wait.

135
00:05:41.341 --> 00:05:43.074
How about dinner tomorrow night?

136
00:05:44.811 --> 00:05:47.245
No cell phones.
no urgent emails.

137
00:05:47.314 --> 00:05:50.081
just a nice bottle of wine.
and a few hours to remind us.

138
00:05:50.583 --> 00:05:52.216
Of what?

139
00:05:52.285 --> 00:05:53.952
How great we are together.

140
00:05:59.993 --> 00:06:02.439
JIM: <i>You know what I was really
thinking when that plane was going down?</i>

141
00:06:02.463 --> 00:06:04.062
"I should have
flown commercial"?

142
00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:06.130
The world needs her.

143
00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:09.201
I mean. who she
is. what she does.

144
00:06:09.269 --> 00:06:10.568
Stephanie matters.

145
00:06:10.637 --> 00:06:12.303
And me? Who am I?

146
00:06:13.340 --> 00:06:15.073
A failed painter?

147
00:06:15.142 --> 00:06:16.775
Ineffectual police artist?

148
00:06:16.843 --> 00:06:18.788
A guy who won't shut
up when I'm trying to hit?

149
00:06:18.812 --> 00:06:20.979
Look. Have you
tried. radical idea.

150
00:06:21.047 --> 00:06:22.325
just telling her how you feel?

151
00:06:22.349 --> 00:06:24.527
How are you supposed
to tell someone that

152
00:06:24.551 --> 00:06:26.318
you've been living
separate lives?

153
00:06:26.386 --> 00:06:28.086
I am no expert on marriage.

154
00:06:28.155 --> 00:06:30.395
as my last two
wives will attest.

155
00:06:30.958 --> 00:06:31.958
but here.

156
00:06:34.661 --> 00:06:35.993
A divorce attorney?

157
00:06:36.062 --> 00:06:38.174
That's the wrong card.
I'm sorry about that.

158
00:06:38.198 --> 00:06:39.438
Sorry. sorry. sorry.

159
00:06:41.235 --> 00:06:42.567
Couples' therapist?

160
00:06:42.636 --> 00:06:44.647
Both my ex-wives
begged me to see him.

161
00:06:44.671 --> 00:06:46.070
That. and hating me.

162
00:06:46.139 --> 00:06:47.617
were the only two things
they had in common.

163
00:06:47.641 --> 00:06:49.173
Now had I listened.

164
00:06:49.242 --> 00:06:51.709
maybe I wouldn't
have needed this card.

165
00:06:51.778 --> 00:06:53.511
Maybe you won't either.

166
00:07:01.822 --> 00:07:03.855
JIM: <i>Ma'am. the more
details you give me.</i>

167
00:07:03.923 --> 00:07:05.390
<i>the better sketch I can draw.</i>

168
00:07:05.459 --> 00:07:06.935
WOMAN: <i>I don't see the point.</i>

169
00:07:06.959 --> 00:07:09.460
I already told the detectives
I couldn't see his face.

170
00:07:09.529 --> 00:07:10.640
He was wearing a mask.

171
00:07:10.664 --> 00:07:12.730
Of President Obama. I know.

172
00:07:12.799 --> 00:07:14.799
But if you can
remember anything.

173
00:07:14.867 --> 00:07:16.834
hair color. eye color.

174
00:07:16.903 --> 00:07:20.504
See. I can create a composite.
which I can give to the detectives.

175
00:07:20.573 --> 00:07:23.274
Now. it's not gonna
bring your husband back.

176
00:07:23.343 --> 00:07:25.143
but it might help
save somebody else's.

177
00:07:25.211 --> 00:07:28.146
We opened that jewelry store
with money from my father.

178
00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:31.516
Why don't we
take a little break?

179
00:07:32.819 --> 00:07:33.885
(CRYING)

180
00:07:35.889 --> 00:07:36.969
(EXHALING)

181
00:07:39.159 --> 00:07:40.199
Powell.

182
00:07:40.260 --> 00:07:41.260
Cho.

183
00:07:42.529 --> 00:07:44.061
Detective Cho.

184
00:07:48.035 --> 00:07:49.501
Day after day.

185
00:07:49.569 --> 00:07:52.037
facing people you
know you just can't help.

186
00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:54.240
How do you do it?

187
00:07:55.409 --> 00:07:57.569
By not asking
myself that question.

188
00:07:59.379 --> 00:08:02.099
Crime's up. It's as
bad as I've seen it.

189
00:08:03.216 --> 00:08:06.536
I wish more people around
here cared as much as you do.

190
00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:08.552
Gun! Gun!

191
00:08:11.591 --> 00:08:12.924
(GUNSHOT)

192
00:08:15.261 --> 00:08:16.527
You all right?

193
00:08:16.596 --> 00:08:17.662
Yeah. You?

194
00:08:17.731 --> 00:08:18.731
Yeah.

195
00:08:24.037 --> 00:08:25.197
The bullet.

196
00:08:25.238 --> 00:08:26.478
Where did it go?

197
00:08:28.074 --> 00:08:30.208
Hey. hey. You all right?

198
00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:32.310
I...

199
00:08:32.379 --> 00:08:33.811
I just need some fresh air.

200
00:09:02.943 --> 00:09:06.243
In the morning. there's that split
second just before you wake up

201
00:09:06.312 --> 00:09:10.247
when the world hasn't
pressed itself in on your chest.

202
00:09:10.317 --> 00:09:12.082
<i>Before you remember your work.</i>

203
00:09:12.151 --> 00:09:14.752
<i>Or the husband you
can't connect with.</i>

204
00:09:14.821 --> 00:09:16.921
<i>Or the kids you
fear you'll disappoint.</i>

205
00:09:19.192 --> 00:09:21.292
(JIM WHISTLING)

206
00:09:21.361 --> 00:09:24.321
<i>But what I woke up to that morning
was something very different.</i>

207
00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:30.446
<i>What I woke up to was a
man I hadn't seen in years.</i>

208
00:09:30.470 --> 00:09:31.802
Beautiful day. huh?

209
00:09:32.939 --> 00:09:34.205
(SIGHS)

210
00:09:35.141 --> 00:09:36.381
Want me to close this?

211
00:09:40.414 --> 00:09:44.114
I've been meaning to fix that.

212
00:09:44.183 --> 00:09:48.620
STEPHANIE: <i>Though Jim seemed
different. I barely had time to wonder why.</i>

213
00:09:48.688 --> 00:09:51.889
And truth is. I barely
had any time at all.

214
00:09:51.959 --> 00:09:54.058
<i>Between work and home.</i>

215
00:09:54.127 --> 00:09:55.771
<i>there weren't enough
hours in the day.</i>

216
00:09:55.795 --> 00:09:57.406
JJ's meeting with the
guidance counselor is at 3:00.

217
00:09:57.430 --> 00:09:58.808
but they might
move it back to 2:00.

218
00:09:58.832 --> 00:10:00.776
so be on call just in case.
Be on call just in case.

219
00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:03.368
Anybody who wants a ride.
now would be the time. Let's go.

220
00:10:04.137 --> 00:10:05.257
Egg's right here.

221
00:10:11.645 --> 00:10:13.845
All right. I will
see you later. JJ.

222
00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:15.146
Daph.

223
00:10:15.816 --> 00:10:17.615
Everything okay?

224
00:10:17.684 --> 00:10:19.962
Look. I can tell there's
something on your mind.

225
00:10:19.986 --> 00:10:21.052
About Lucas?

226
00:10:21.654 --> 00:10:23.487
Or the plane crash?

227
00:10:23.556 --> 00:10:25.768
We did just have a near-death
experience. it's bound to change you.

228
00:10:25.792 --> 00:10:27.124
That whore!

229
00:10:29.963 --> 00:10:30.995
Or not.

230
00:10:32.065 --> 00:10:34.432
Hi. baby! Excuse me. Hi.

231
00:10:34.501 --> 00:10:35.766
Daphne. You're back.

232
00:10:35.835 --> 00:10:37.475
Yeah. and just in
time. too. apparently.

233
00:10:37.504 --> 00:10:39.515
Yeah. I'm really glad that
you survived the accident.

234
00:10:39.539 --> 00:10:41.350
Those memorial assemblies
are super depressing.

235
00:10:41.374 --> 00:10:43.534
I know. I remember the
one we had for your virginity.

236
00:10:43.576 --> 00:10:45.477
What was it. like.
two years ago?

237
00:10:46.346 --> 00:10:47.586
(FAKES LAUGHING) See ya.

238
00:10:48.148 --> 00:10:49.447
See ya.

239
00:10:49.515 --> 00:10:51.115
Hey. Hi.

240
00:10:51.184 --> 00:10:52.249
I'm so glad you're back.

241
00:10:52.318 --> 00:10:53.618
Me too.

242
00:10:53.687 --> 00:10:56.287
How are you? I'm better now.

243
00:10:56.356 --> 00:10:57.500
I'll hook up with
you later. okay?

244
00:10:57.524 --> 00:10:58.556
Okay.

245
00:11:00.761 --> 00:11:02.293
Hey. Daph.

246
00:11:02.362 --> 00:11:03.461
Nice view.

247
00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:05.797
I can't tell what's cuter.

248
00:11:05.866 --> 00:11:08.144
The fact that Lucas has no
idea Lindsay's hitting on him

249
00:11:08.168 --> 00:11:10.568
or that he's too
into me to see it.

250
00:11:12.205 --> 00:11:15.473
KATIE: The board's waiting
for you in the conference room.

251
00:11:15.542 --> 00:11:17.920
Crap! I'm having dinner with Jim
and I forgot to make reservations.

252
00:11:17.944 --> 00:11:19.443
Could you? Yes.

253
00:11:19.512 --> 00:11:21.991
All right. someplace where they
won't give the table away if I'm late.

254
00:11:22.015 --> 00:11:23.915
Yes.

255
00:11:23.984 --> 00:11:26.995
But amid the untold natural
resources of the Amazon basin.

256
00:11:27.019 --> 00:11:28.886
we have uncovered. perhaps.

257
00:11:28.955 --> 00:11:30.455
the crown jewel.

258
00:11:30.524 --> 00:11:31.856
The <i>Trilsetum coronis.</i>

259
00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:34.360
A plant?

260
00:11:35.895 --> 00:11:39.215
You're wasting the
board's time on a plant?

261
00:11:39.866 --> 00:11:42.534
Carbon-fourteen dating
traces the <i>Trilsetum coronis</i>

262
00:11:42.602 --> 00:11:44.035
back to the Pleistocene Epoch.

263
00:11:44.103 --> 00:11:46.081
and as we know. that was...

264
00:11:46.105 --> 00:11:48.417
I stand corrected. You're wasting
the board's time on a really old plant.

265
00:11:48.441 --> 00:11:49.607
Dr. Chiles.

266
00:11:49.675 --> 00:11:51.554
You'll get your turn to
waste the board's time.

267
00:11:51.578 --> 00:11:52.877
CHAIRMAN: Indeed.

268
00:11:52.946 --> 00:11:54.211
Continue. Dr. Powell.

269
00:11:55.649 --> 00:11:58.315
Our facilities in Belem
are already experimenting

270
00:11:58.384 --> 00:12:01.052
with practical applications
across our divisions.

271
00:12:01.121 --> 00:12:03.654
Pharmaceuticals.
papers. green fuel.

272
00:12:03.723 --> 00:12:06.925
I'd bet money there is
nothing this plant can't do.

273
00:12:08.228 --> 00:12:10.673
I want to buy out the
whole place. One hour.

274
00:12:10.697 --> 00:12:12.675
And I want you to take a break.

275
00:12:12.699 --> 00:12:14.859
Sorry. I'm not allowed
to leave you alone here...

276
00:12:16.770 --> 00:12:18.135
for more than an hour.

277
00:12:41.627 --> 00:12:42.627
(SIGHS)

278
00:12:56.276 --> 00:12:57.441
Come on.

279
00:13:13.827 --> 00:13:15.026
(LAUGHING)

280
00:13:20.032 --> 00:13:21.032
(WHOOPS)

281
00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:28.840
(POWERING UP)

282
00:13:41.554 --> 00:13:42.720
Dr. King.

283
00:13:42.789 --> 00:13:43.833
Stephanie.

284
00:13:43.857 --> 00:13:45.623
I've been looking for you.

285
00:13:45.691 --> 00:13:46.824
Sorry. I had to...

286
00:13:47.994 --> 00:13:49.138
step out for a second.

287
00:13:49.162 --> 00:13:50.305
No need to be defensive.

288
00:13:50.329 --> 00:13:52.897
I'm not that much of
a taskmaster. am I?

289
00:13:52.965 --> 00:13:55.332
Don't answer that.
At least not honestly.

290
00:13:55.401 --> 00:13:57.921
No. the reason I was looking
for you is I have some good news.

291
00:13:59.572 --> 00:14:01.239
The chairman's intrigued.

292
00:14:01.307 --> 00:14:02.807
By? You.

293
00:14:02.876 --> 00:14:05.243
Your very old
plant. specifically.

294
00:14:07.012 --> 00:14:08.946
He's flying in tonight.

295
00:14:09.014 --> 00:14:11.415
Wants an in-depth
presentation over drinks.

296
00:14:12.485 --> 00:14:14.518
Drinks?

297
00:14:14.587 --> 00:14:17.922
A social custom commonly
enjoyed between adults.

298
00:14:18.992 --> 00:14:21.152
He wants to fund your research.

299
00:14:23.362 --> 00:14:25.597
Don't fracture
anything jumping for joy.

300
00:14:25.665 --> 00:14:27.364
(LAUGHS)

301
00:14:27.433 --> 00:14:28.532
Can't wait.

302
00:14:28.601 --> 00:14:29.812
I'll see you later.
We'll leave from here.

303
00:14:29.836 --> 00:14:31.636
Okay. All right.

304
00:14:35.208 --> 00:14:37.141
(SIGHING)

305
00:14:37.210 --> 00:14:39.254
I mean. if this is
a surprise party.

306
00:14:39.278 --> 00:14:41.879
I'd say that the
turnout's a bit depressing.

307
00:14:41.948 --> 00:14:43.280
It's not.

308
00:14:43.349 --> 00:14:46.749
There's something I got
to show you. watch this.

309
00:14:47.921 --> 00:14:49.465
You know. I'm no Hideki Matsui

310
00:14:49.489 --> 00:14:52.849
but it might be a little easier
if you actually used a bat.

311
00:15:00.065 --> 00:15:01.965
Ha!

312
00:15:02.034 --> 00:15:04.413
You've been taking magic
classes at the Learning Annex?

313
00:15:04.437 --> 00:15:07.105
It's not magic classes.

314
00:15:07.173 --> 00:15:10.252
Whoa. I think we're stepping over
the line here. Where did you get that?

315
00:15:10.276 --> 00:15:11.643
Precinct supply closet.

316
00:15:11.711 --> 00:15:13.144
Surprisingly poor lock.

317
00:15:13.213 --> 00:15:14.373
What do you need that for?

318
00:15:14.414 --> 00:15:15.713
I don't. You do.

319
00:15:15.782 --> 00:15:17.148
(COCKS GUN)

320
00:15:17.216 --> 00:15:18.783
I need you to shoot me.

321
00:15:21.087 --> 00:15:22.353
(CLEARING THROAT)

322
00:15:25.992 --> 00:15:27.325
(PHONE RINGS)

323
00:15:27.394 --> 00:15:29.026
JIM: <i>Hey. Steph.</i>

324
00:15:29.095 --> 00:15:31.996
Look. date night's not
looking so promising.

325
00:15:32.065 --> 00:15:33.175
<i>Chairman's in town. and he...</i>

326
00:15:33.199 --> 00:15:34.498
No. that's fine.

327
00:15:34.567 --> 00:15:35.733
Oh.

328
00:15:35.802 --> 00:15:36.934
Okay.

329
00:15:37.403 --> 00:15:38.836
Well.

330
00:15:38.905 --> 00:15:41.005
I will get home
as soon as I can.

331
00:15:41.074 --> 00:15:43.141
We'll grab some take-out.
light some candles.

332
00:15:43.209 --> 00:15:44.286
and still have our night.

333
00:15:44.310 --> 00:15:46.110
<i>Absolutely.</i> Okay.

334
00:15:49.382 --> 00:15:50.915
Okay. let's do this.

335
00:15:50.984 --> 00:15:52.394
I can't believe
I'm gonna kill you.

336
00:15:52.418 --> 00:15:53.851
You're not gonna
kill me. George.

337
00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:55.040
You're just gonna shoot me.

338
00:15:55.088 --> 00:15:56.454
I'm a D.A.

339
00:15:56.522 --> 00:15:58.534
And according to the
law. kind of the same thing.

340
00:15:58.558 --> 00:16:00.558
I told you. I did
this yesterday.

341
00:16:00.626 --> 00:16:02.360
I just have to see
if I can do it again.

342
00:16:02.429 --> 00:16:05.062
What if you can't?
Where does that leave us?

343
00:16:05.131 --> 00:16:07.410
You dead and me showering
with a bunch of guys

344
00:16:07.434 --> 00:16:08.877
I suddenly wish I
hadn't put away.

345
00:16:08.901 --> 00:16:11.168
Something extraordinary
is happening to me.

346
00:16:11.237 --> 00:16:14.204
Something impossible.

347
00:16:14.273 --> 00:16:17.608
And I just... I need your
help to figure out what it is.

348
00:16:18.511 --> 00:16:20.011
Please.

349
00:16:26.586 --> 00:16:28.252
Okay. George.

350
00:16:28.321 --> 00:16:29.854
just aim

351
00:16:29.923 --> 00:16:30.988
and fire.

352
00:16:38.664 --> 00:16:39.904
I'm not... I'm not...

353
00:16:47.774 --> 00:16:48.805
George.

354
00:16:50.176 --> 00:16:51.376
George.

355
00:16:52.779 --> 00:16:53.911
Dr. Powell.

356
00:16:53.980 --> 00:16:55.446
Dr. King left a message.

357
00:16:55.514 --> 00:16:57.981
Said to meet them at
the chairman's hotel.

358
00:16:58.050 --> 00:16:59.650
I'd take the freeway
if I were you.

359
00:16:59.719 --> 00:17:01.785
Surface streets are a
mess this time of day.

360
00:17:06.960 --> 00:17:09.160
And that's when it happened.

361
00:17:09.228 --> 00:17:13.063
<i>In the world of science. we call
it an unexplained phenomenon.</i>

362
00:17:13.133 --> 00:17:15.633
(WHOOSHING)

363
00:17:15.702 --> 00:17:19.170
An occurrence so
random and bizarre.

364
00:17:19.239 --> 00:17:21.305
<i>that it defies explanation.</i>

365
00:17:23.276 --> 00:17:24.875
(MUFFLED BOOM)

366
00:17:49.702 --> 00:17:52.569
<i>And in a life short on time</i>

367
00:17:52.638 --> 00:17:54.338
<i>I suddenly found myself...</i>

368
00:17:55.474 --> 00:17:56.506
<i>fast.</i>

369
00:17:59.044 --> 00:18:01.178
(CARS HONKING)

370
00:18:09.255 --> 00:18:12.868
For the next few weeks. I did my
best to act as if nothing had changed.

371
00:18:12.892 --> 00:18:15.292
<i>I'd kiss my family goodbye.</i>

372
00:18:15.361 --> 00:18:17.681
<i>counting the minutes
till I could meet George</i>

373
00:18:17.730 --> 00:18:20.164
to write the owner's
manual for my new ride.

374
00:18:20.233 --> 00:18:21.376
Most of them can fly.

375
00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:22.566
I can't fly.

376
00:18:22.635 --> 00:18:24.046
I remember when you
couldn't catch bullets either.

377
00:18:24.070 --> 00:18:25.636
I can't fly.

378
00:18:25.705 --> 00:18:27.872
Just take a running jump.

379
00:18:27.941 --> 00:18:31.042
Look. get a head
of steam. right.

380
00:18:31.110 --> 00:18:33.944
and you just think like
something that can fly.

381
00:18:34.012 --> 00:18:35.213
(MIMICS PLANE)

382
00:18:36.449 --> 00:18:37.559
That's easy for you to say.

383
00:18:37.583 --> 00:18:39.683
but if this doesn't
work. I'm roadkill.

384
00:18:39.752 --> 00:18:42.620
From the guy that begged
me to shoot him the other day.

385
00:18:46.959 --> 00:18:48.126
All right.

386
00:18:52.131 --> 00:18:53.163
Just...

387
00:19:00.005 --> 00:19:01.505
(YELLING)

388
00:19:04.543 --> 00:19:05.976
(SCREAMING)

389
00:19:11.584 --> 00:19:13.184
(DOG BARKING)

390
00:19:19.292 --> 00:19:20.391
GEORGE: Okay!

391
00:19:21.961 --> 00:19:23.127
You can't fly!

392
00:19:40.747 --> 00:19:41.812
Holy...

393
00:19:43.449 --> 00:19:44.915
But you can jump.

394
00:19:46.419 --> 00:19:48.319
You can jump. man!

395
00:19:48.988 --> 00:19:50.254
Okay. okay. okay.

396
00:19:50.323 --> 00:19:51.967
STEPHANIE: <i>I wasn't sure
what was happening with Jim.</i>

397
00:19:51.991 --> 00:19:53.724
You all right?

398
00:19:53.793 --> 00:19:55.904
But I had to share my
new abilities with someone.

399
00:19:55.928 --> 00:19:57.428
A peer.

400
00:19:57.496 --> 00:19:59.563
Someone who had
the scientific capacity

401
00:19:59.631 --> 00:20:02.266
<i>to understand what
was happening to me.</i>

402
00:20:02.335 --> 00:20:04.067
Can I talk to you?
In confidence?

403
00:20:04.136 --> 00:20:06.982
Oh. my God. you're firing
me. Are you firing me?

404
00:20:07.006 --> 00:20:09.318
STEPHANIE: <i>Admittedly.
I might have chosen better.</i>

405
00:20:09.342 --> 00:20:10.774
No.

406
00:20:10.843 --> 00:20:12.387
No. I'm not firing you. Oh. God.

407
00:20:12.411 --> 00:20:14.578
This is about me.

408
00:20:14.646 --> 00:20:16.624
Okay. are you gonna tell
me something really personal

409
00:20:16.648 --> 00:20:18.727
like we're best friends. even
though I'm just your lab tech.

410
00:20:18.751 --> 00:20:23.287
'cause that would totally validate
everything I've been working on in therapy.

411
00:20:23.356 --> 00:20:26.958
No. you know that superhero thingy
you keep in your cubicle downstairs?

412
00:20:27.026 --> 00:20:29.271
Oh. Kitty Pryde? Yeah.
she's my favorite X-Man.

413
00:20:29.295 --> 00:20:30.761
Well. X-Woman technically.

414
00:20:30.829 --> 00:20:32.362
(WHOOSHING)

415
00:20:33.366 --> 00:20:34.932
I'm fast.

416
00:20:40.707 --> 00:20:43.040
I can't believe I'm here...

417
00:20:43.109 --> 00:20:44.641
(MUFFLED BOOM)

418
00:20:46.612 --> 00:20:47.852
doing this.

419
00:20:48.447 --> 00:20:50.014
Accepting this!

420
00:20:51.951 --> 00:20:55.511
How does your body cut
through the wind shear?

421
00:20:57.323 --> 00:21:00.524
Why doesn't the Coulomb
friction singe your clothes?

422
00:21:02.027 --> 00:21:05.096
Are you generating some
kind of charged plasma field

423
00:21:05.164 --> 00:21:06.463
from the kinetic energy?

424
00:21:08.801 --> 00:21:12.469
Is that why incoming debris isn't
sandblasting off your corneas?

425
00:21:17.009 --> 00:21:18.175
(PANTING)

426
00:21:18.244 --> 00:21:19.443
How'd I do?

427
00:21:19.512 --> 00:21:22.813
You were doing a
mile every six seconds.

428
00:21:22.881 --> 00:21:25.360
I thought I was faster
than that. Oh. my God.

429
00:21:25.384 --> 00:21:27.362
(GASPS) Oh. my
God! The Olympics!

430
00:21:27.386 --> 00:21:28.830
You should totally enter.
Where are they this year?

431
00:21:28.854 --> 00:21:30.532
Korea? They're always in Korea.

432
00:21:30.556 --> 00:21:33.490
No. no. Katie. Katie. I'm not
interested in the Olympics.

433
00:21:33.559 --> 00:21:34.803
Okay. what are
you interested in?

434
00:21:34.827 --> 00:21:36.159
Making time.

435
00:21:36.228 --> 00:21:38.373
KATIE: Thanks to your
increased metabolic rate.

436
00:21:38.397 --> 00:21:41.332
your life is like a
never-ending Spin class.

437
00:21:41.400 --> 00:21:45.469
So. despite the need
for massive caloric intake.

438
00:21:45.538 --> 00:21:48.472
you're gonna be a size
zero for the rest of your life.

439
00:21:48.541 --> 00:21:49.840
I hate you.

440
00:21:49.909 --> 00:21:52.176
Oh. my gosh! It's already 3:00.

441
00:21:52.245 --> 00:21:53.844
I've got to. well.

442
00:21:54.213 --> 00:21:55.245
run.

443
00:21:55.314 --> 00:21:56.314
(WHOOSHING)

444
00:21:59.719 --> 00:22:00.929
Mom. Hi.

445
00:22:00.953 --> 00:22:02.564
What are you doing out here?

446
00:22:02.588 --> 00:22:05.823
I told you I would make some
time to help with your school work.

447
00:22:05.892 --> 00:22:06.924
So what do we have here?

448
00:22:08.027 --> 00:22:09.794
Math.

449
00:22:09.862 --> 00:22:13.464
All right. "If a bullet train leaves
New York going 350 miles per hour..."

450
00:22:13.533 --> 00:22:15.299
(LAUGHS)

451
00:22:15.367 --> 00:22:17.534
I think I can help
you on this one.

452
00:22:17.603 --> 00:22:19.070
GEORGE: Here's
what we know so far.

453
00:22:19.138 --> 00:22:21.378
You can jump just over a
quarter mile in a single leap.

454
00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:22.640
A single what?

455
00:22:24.277 --> 00:22:26.310
Fine. Single bound.

456
00:22:26.379 --> 00:22:27.923
No discernible
increase in foot speed.

457
00:22:27.947 --> 00:22:30.314
However. you can
lift just in the area

458
00:22:30.383 --> 00:22:32.182
of 11.000 pounds.

459
00:22:32.251 --> 00:22:34.217
and you can catch bullets.

460
00:22:34.287 --> 00:22:37.254
So have you talked to Steph about
this? Told her what you can do?

461
00:22:37.323 --> 00:22:38.323
Nope.

462
00:22:38.391 --> 00:22:39.757
Jim.

463
00:22:39.826 --> 00:22:41.391
she's your wife.

464
00:22:41.460 --> 00:22:43.420
You have to bring her
into this cone of silence.

465
00:22:43.462 --> 00:22:44.494
What is that?

466
00:22:44.563 --> 00:22:46.497
(CHATTER ON RADIO)

467
00:22:46.566 --> 00:22:48.143
What are you doing
with a police scanner?

468
00:22:48.167 --> 00:22:51.313
I have these abilities. I should
be using them for something. right?

469
00:22:51.337 --> 00:22:54.905
Like stopping these psychos in
Obama masks killing innocent people.

470
00:22:54.974 --> 00:22:56.473
Hold on.

471
00:22:56.542 --> 00:22:59.242
All we have learned so far
is that we have a lot to learn.

472
00:22:59.312 --> 00:23:01.211
You're special. but
you're not invincible.

473
00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:02.657
I don't even know if you're
vincible. (CELL PHONE RINGING)

474
00:23:02.681 --> 00:23:04.493
George! Hold on. It's Stephanie.

475
00:23:04.517 --> 00:23:05.517
Tell her.

476
00:23:05.585 --> 00:23:08.118
JIM: <i>Hello?</i> Hey.

477
00:23:08.187 --> 00:23:11.255
I finished work. I
tutored JJ. and I...

478
00:23:11.323 --> 00:23:12.590
It isn't even 4:00 yet.

479
00:23:12.658 --> 00:23:14.602
And I can jump a
quarter of a mile.

480
00:23:14.626 --> 00:23:17.627
I'm moving kind of fast today.

481
00:23:17.696 --> 00:23:20.130
Anyway. the kids
aren't here and...

482
00:23:20.199 --> 00:23:21.709
Remember what we'd do sometimes

483
00:23:21.733 --> 00:23:24.501
when we both had
a free afternoon?

484
00:23:24.569 --> 00:23:26.403
(STEPHANIE SIGHS)

485
00:23:26.471 --> 00:23:28.871
It's nice to remember
we're good at that.

486
00:23:29.675 --> 00:23:30.875
Yeah.

487
00:23:30.943 --> 00:23:33.010
That's a nice
thing to be good at.

488
00:23:33.078 --> 00:23:34.578
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

489
00:23:35.681 --> 00:23:37.180
You seem different to me.

490
00:23:39.351 --> 00:23:40.450
Me?

491
00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:41.552
Yeah.

492
00:23:43.188 --> 00:23:45.508
I thought that about you.

493
00:23:46.358 --> 00:23:48.058
You have?

494
00:23:48.126 --> 00:23:50.407
Jim. how could I not notice?

495
00:23:51.029 --> 00:23:52.529
I mean. you seem...

496
00:23:54.233 --> 00:23:55.433
happy.

497
00:23:56.469 --> 00:23:57.501
(SIGHS)

498
00:23:57.570 --> 00:23:59.569
What?

499
00:23:59.638 --> 00:24:02.506
My life wasn't turning
out the way I'd hoped.

500
00:24:02.574 --> 00:24:05.743
Meanwhile. you're running
around. living your dreams...

501
00:24:06.646 --> 00:24:09.479
Yes. I was running.

502
00:24:09.548 --> 00:24:11.993
so much that I was
falling short at everything.

503
00:24:12.017 --> 00:24:13.150
"Falling short"?

504
00:24:13.719 --> 00:24:14.751
Honey.

505
00:24:15.588 --> 00:24:17.354
who could keep up with you?

506
00:24:17.423 --> 00:24:20.157
Well. you couldn't
because you stopped trying.

507
00:24:23.029 --> 00:24:24.528
(EXHALES)

508
00:24:30.936 --> 00:24:32.903
All right. we both
stopped trying.

509
00:24:37.743 --> 00:24:39.922
You wanna know what's
going on with your daughter?

510
00:24:39.946 --> 00:24:42.046
Hmm?

511
00:24:42.114 --> 00:24:46.516
She's afraid she's gonna lose her
boyfriend to a girl that'll sleep with him.

512
00:24:46.585 --> 00:24:48.719
because she's not ready to yet.

513
00:24:49.422 --> 00:24:50.888
And JJ.

514
00:24:50.956 --> 00:24:52.789
He's struggling with school.

515
00:24:52.858 --> 00:24:55.792
because the school wants
to put him in remedial classes.

516
00:24:55.861 --> 00:24:59.430
but you won't accept the fact that
your son has a learning disability.

517
00:25:01.534 --> 00:25:02.945
Now. you may have
known all these things

518
00:25:02.969 --> 00:25:05.602
if you were home for more
than 20 minutes a night.

519
00:25:06.538 --> 00:25:08.271
Right.

520
00:25:08.340 --> 00:25:10.085
Because it's the
dream of every wife

521
00:25:10.109 --> 00:25:12.977
to work 80 hours a week
to support her family.

522
00:25:13.045 --> 00:25:14.411
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

523
00:25:20.452 --> 00:25:22.164
JIM: <i>Hello?</i> Guess what?

524
00:25:22.188 --> 00:25:23.820
You got your wish.

525
00:25:23.889 --> 00:25:26.849
Obama mask. Robbery
in progress. You're on.

526
00:25:27.460 --> 00:25:29.059
<i>Okay. Perp...</i>

527
00:25:29.127 --> 00:25:30.271
Perp. I like that.

528
00:25:30.295 --> 00:25:31.428
(CHATTER ON RADIO)

529
00:25:31.497 --> 00:25:34.097
Perp headed north
on Twelfth and Fig.

530
00:25:34.567 --> 00:25:35.598
Okay.

531
00:25:39.204 --> 00:25:40.804
I have to go.

532
00:25:40.873 --> 00:25:42.606
(SIRENS WAILING)

533
00:25:43.976 --> 00:25:45.309
(SCREAMING)

534
00:25:52.184 --> 00:25:53.517
(PANTING)

535
00:25:55.654 --> 00:25:57.821
Hey. Hey. George.

536
00:25:57.890 --> 00:26:00.624
I'm on top of the Simonson Building
heading north. Which way now?

537
00:26:03.095 --> 00:26:04.461
GEORGE: It's a left.

538
00:26:04.529 --> 00:26:05.941
Are you sure you don't
wanna use the freeway route?

539
00:26:05.965 --> 00:26:07.264
'Cause it looks much faster.

540
00:26:07.332 --> 00:26:09.666
I'm not worried
about traffic. George.

541
00:26:18.911 --> 00:26:20.677
(TIRES SQUEALING)

542
00:26:54.179 --> 00:26:55.945
You're going away
for a long time.

543
00:26:56.014 --> 00:26:57.314
(GUNSHOT)

544
00:27:04.223 --> 00:27:05.489
(LAUGHING)

545
00:27:18.070 --> 00:27:19.169
George.

546
00:27:20.239 --> 00:27:21.971
Help me. George.

547
00:27:22.040 --> 00:27:23.172
I've been shot.

548
00:27:29.014 --> 00:27:30.714
You're awake.

549
00:27:30.783 --> 00:27:32.961
Look. you had some blood loss.
but the bullet didn't penetrate too far.

550
00:27:32.985 --> 00:27:35.225
We sewed you up.
You're as good... "We"?

551
00:27:35.588 --> 00:27:36.920
No. George.

552
00:27:36.989 --> 00:27:38.366
Don't tell me... Where
was I supposed to take you?

553
00:27:38.390 --> 00:27:39.689
To the hospital?

554
00:27:39.758 --> 00:27:41.536
And explain to the attending
why a large caliber bullet

555
00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:43.671
only penetrated a quarter of
an inch through your scalp?

556
00:27:43.695 --> 00:27:45.707
But she'll never understand
what's happening to me.

557
00:27:45.731 --> 00:27:47.997
Oh. I think you'll be surprised.

558
00:27:52.204 --> 00:27:53.881
Remember the sketch
of me in your studio?

559
00:27:53.905 --> 00:27:55.805
The one you drew
on our first date?

560
00:27:55.874 --> 00:27:56.907
Yeah.

561
00:27:58.410 --> 00:28:00.043
(WHOOSHING)

562
00:28:03.448 --> 00:28:05.015
You two are freaky.

563
00:28:07.219 --> 00:28:08.552
But how?

564
00:28:08.620 --> 00:28:11.188
(STEPHANIE SIGHS)

565
00:28:11.256 --> 00:28:14.458
You know. I've been racking my
brain and the only possible variable...

566
00:28:14.526 --> 00:28:15.559
The plane crash?

567
00:28:15.627 --> 00:28:17.694
It's the only explanation.

568
00:28:17.763 --> 00:28:19.741
And when our plane went down.

569
00:28:19.765 --> 00:28:23.033
<i>the water had a phosphorescence.</i>

570
00:28:23.101 --> 00:28:26.336
<i>At the time. I thought it
was gasoline from the plane.</i>

571
00:28:26.405 --> 00:28:29.038
<i>But gas floats on water.</i>

572
00:28:29.107 --> 00:28:31.174
<i>This didn't.</i>

573
00:28:31.243 --> 00:28:34.763
It's the only thing that makes
sense. If any of this makes any sense.

574
00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:37.380
But we were all in the water.

575
00:28:38.450 --> 00:28:40.083
(PHONE RINGING)

576
00:28:43.556 --> 00:28:44.587
Hello?

577
00:28:45.057 --> 00:28:46.323
Daphne?

578
00:28:46.391 --> 00:28:48.511
Calm down. honey. Where are you?

579
00:28:50.129 --> 00:28:51.828
DAPHNE: I called Dad.

580
00:28:53.265 --> 00:28:55.365
He has a headache.

581
00:28:55.433 --> 00:28:56.699
He's home resting.

582
00:28:56.768 --> 00:28:59.970
I just usually talk to him
about this sort of thing.

583
00:29:00.605 --> 00:29:01.738
I know.

584
00:29:01.807 --> 00:29:03.373
(SIGHS)

585
00:29:03.442 --> 00:29:04.907
Before the game.

586
00:29:04.976 --> 00:29:06.776
I was on the court.

587
00:29:06.845 --> 00:29:08.278
<i>With Emily.</i>

588
00:29:11.350 --> 00:29:13.883
EMILY: Are you not going
to say something to her?

589
00:29:13.952 --> 00:29:17.421
She was all over Lucas the
entire time you were in Mexico.

590
00:29:17.489 --> 00:29:19.456
Or wherever.

591
00:29:19.525 --> 00:29:21.858
This is a boyfriend problem?

592
00:29:21.927 --> 00:29:23.060
Wait.

593
00:29:23.128 --> 00:29:25.028
Stay away from Lucas.

594
00:29:25.097 --> 00:29:26.429
He was talking to me.

595
00:29:26.498 --> 00:29:28.776
Okay. it took me all of last
year to get Lucas to notice me.

596
00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:31.034
Maybe if you weren't so
concerned with losing Lucas.

597
00:29:31.103 --> 00:29:32.702
you'd notice that
you already have.

598
00:29:32.771 --> 00:29:33.882
What do you mean?

599
00:29:33.906 --> 00:29:35.216
LINDSAY: <i>You're so clueless.</i>

600
00:29:35.240 --> 00:29:37.340
<i>I can't believe I
actually feel bad for you.</i>

601
00:29:40.512 --> 00:29:41.678
Bad for me. why?

602
00:29:43.449 --> 00:29:45.182
I didn't say anything.

603
00:29:49.221 --> 00:29:50.486
DAPHNE: <i>And then</i>

604
00:29:50.555 --> 00:29:51.821
<i>the game started.</i>

605
00:29:51.890 --> 00:29:54.202
EMILY: <i>She's not gonna
pass. She never passes to me.</i>

606
00:29:54.226 --> 00:29:56.960
GIRL 1: <i>What is wrong with her?</i>

607
00:29:57.028 --> 00:29:58.272
GIRL 2: <i>Daphne.
what are you doing?</i>

608
00:29:58.296 --> 00:30:00.875
REFEREE: <i>This game
blows. I need a drink.</i>

609
00:30:00.899 --> 00:30:02.510
BOY 1: <i>She wants to
be a basketball player?</i>

610
00:30:02.534 --> 00:30:04.494
BOY 2: <i>We're gonna lose.</i>

611
00:30:06.371 --> 00:30:08.471
DAPHNE: <i>I wasn't
hearing my thoughts.</i>

612
00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:10.473
I was hearing theirs.

613
00:30:10.542 --> 00:30:12.809
You probably think
I'm losing my mind! I...

614
00:30:12.877 --> 00:30:15.812
No. No. I actually
believe every word.

615
00:30:17.249 --> 00:30:19.861
Look. honey. there's
something I need to tell you.

616
00:30:19.885 --> 00:30:22.986
Something extraordinary
has happened.

617
00:30:23.055 --> 00:30:25.989
is happening. to us.

618
00:30:26.058 --> 00:30:28.758
And you may be
experiencing things. too.

619
00:30:28.827 --> 00:30:31.361
that you don't even
understand entirely.

620
00:30:32.363 --> 00:30:33.430
JJ?

621
00:30:34.099 --> 00:30:36.099
This is unbelievable.

622
00:30:36.168 --> 00:30:39.008
My whole family gets dipped in
some super water and all I get...

623
00:30:39.338 --> 00:30:40.338
is wet.

624
00:30:40.405 --> 00:30:41.671
So. you haven't...

625
00:30:41.740 --> 00:30:43.974
No. Dad. I haven't.

626
00:30:44.042 --> 00:30:46.343
I am still plain old JJ.

627
00:30:46.412 --> 00:30:48.356
You know. the dumb
one. Don't say that. kiddo.

628
00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:50.992
DAPHNE: Okay. can we just
stop talking about this? Please.

629
00:30:51.016 --> 00:30:52.649
STEPHANIE: Daphne.

630
00:30:52.718 --> 00:30:55.029
You're telepathic. I think this is
something we should talk about.

631
00:30:55.053 --> 00:30:57.133
What happened to me
only happened once.

632
00:30:57.189 --> 00:30:58.399
So. as far as I'm concerned.

633
00:30:58.423 --> 00:31:00.383
I'm in the same boat as JJ here.

634
00:31:00.459 --> 00:31:03.026
Just as boring as
I was last week.

635
00:31:03.094 --> 00:31:04.494
Daphne. I can help you.

636
00:31:04.563 --> 00:31:06.007
The more we begin to
understand about our abilities...

637
00:31:06.031 --> 00:31:07.530
I don't want new abilities!

638
00:31:07.599 --> 00:31:09.944
High school is
hard enough as it is!

639
00:31:09.968 --> 00:31:12.736
Why are we having
this meeting anyway?

640
00:31:12.805 --> 00:31:15.683
So you two can convince
yourselves that you're different?

641
00:31:15.707 --> 00:31:18.241
'Cause you can catch
bullets and you can run fast?

642
00:31:18.310 --> 00:31:19.550
All right. that's enough.

643
00:31:19.611 --> 00:31:21.912
We go on vacations to reconnect.

644
00:31:21.980 --> 00:31:24.714
Why would we want to
connect in the first place?

645
00:31:24.783 --> 00:31:27.183
To watch Mom stress about work?

646
00:31:27.252 --> 00:31:30.520
Or watch Dad mope around
like he lost a winning lottery ticket?

647
00:31:30.589 --> 00:31:32.989
Look. even JJ can
see it. and JJ's an idiot!

648
00:31:33.058 --> 00:31:35.569
Hey. that's it! Go to
your room. right now!

649
00:31:35.593 --> 00:31:37.105
All the trips and all the talks

650
00:31:37.129 --> 00:31:40.363
couldn't save this family
because this family isn't broken!

651
00:31:40.431 --> 00:31:41.798
You two are!

652
00:31:52.778 --> 00:31:54.144
She's right. isn't she?

653
00:31:56.381 --> 00:31:57.414
Yes.

654
00:32:06.892 --> 00:32:08.491
CHO: And what's this?

655
00:32:08.560 --> 00:32:11.895
We got lucky. a witness saw
this guy fleeing that police pursuit.

656
00:32:11.963 --> 00:32:13.074
Witness? I hadn't heard.

657
00:32:13.098 --> 00:32:14.765
I already ran him
through the database.

658
00:32:14.833 --> 00:32:18.401
Guy's name is Reed Koblenz.

659
00:32:18.470 --> 00:32:20.604
He jumped bail last
month in Michigan.

660
00:32:20.672 --> 00:32:23.484
And then this woman named
Sally Downs posted his bond.

661
00:32:23.508 --> 00:32:27.109
Hey. we got a lead on the jewelry
store perp. Nice work. Powell.

662
00:32:29.781 --> 00:32:31.280
Having trouble saying goodbye?

663
00:32:31.349 --> 00:32:32.916
I thought I'd just tag along.

664
00:32:32.985 --> 00:32:34.885
You know. as back-up.

665
00:32:34.953 --> 00:32:36.619
I like your enthusiasm.

666
00:32:36.688 --> 00:32:39.449
but why don't you leave the crime
fighting to those of us with guns?

667
00:32:40.091 --> 00:32:41.290
(SCOFFS)

668
00:32:50.368 --> 00:32:51.901
(WHOOPING)

669
00:32:56.041 --> 00:32:58.442
I don't know what's going
on with me right now.

670
00:32:58.510 --> 00:33:00.177
Well. that makes two of us.

671
00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:03.020
What's wrong?

672
00:33:05.517 --> 00:33:06.850
I'll be fine.

673
00:33:07.886 --> 00:33:09.152
It's probably just some

674
00:33:09.220 --> 00:33:11.260
post-traumatic stress from
the crash or something.

675
00:33:12.691 --> 00:33:14.691
I'm really glad I came here.

676
00:33:20.699 --> 00:33:22.231
You feel nice.

677
00:33:22.300 --> 00:33:23.677
LUCAS: <i>I gotta get out of here.</i>

678
00:33:23.701 --> 00:33:26.113
<i>I was supposed to
meet Emily an hour ago.</i>

679
00:33:26.137 --> 00:33:27.604
What?

680
00:33:27.672 --> 00:33:29.383
I didn't say anything. No. no.

681
00:33:29.407 --> 00:33:31.608
Emily? My best friend. Emily?

682
00:33:31.677 --> 00:33:33.610
Yeah. What about her?

683
00:33:33.678 --> 00:33:35.178
You're supposed
to meet up with her?

684
00:33:35.247 --> 00:33:37.447
No. What do you mean?

685
00:33:37.515 --> 00:33:38.635
<i>How did she know that?</i>

686
00:33:40.018 --> 00:33:42.852
Lucas. why are you seeing Emily?

687
00:33:42.921 --> 00:33:45.041
<i>Did Emily tell her
we were hooking up?</i>

688
00:33:45.924 --> 00:33:47.624
Oh. my God! You're
sleeping with her!

689
00:33:47.692 --> 00:33:50.071
No. Daph. come on.
She's. like. your best friend.

690
00:33:50.095 --> 00:33:52.829
That's why everybody
thinks I'm so stupid!

691
00:33:52.897 --> 00:33:54.697
You said you were okay to wait!

692
00:33:54.766 --> 00:33:57.334
I am. Of course. I am.

693
00:33:59.504 --> 00:34:01.404
Thanks for telling me
how you really feel.

694
00:34:02.674 --> 00:34:04.341
I appreciate your honesty.

695
00:34:05.577 --> 00:34:06.877
Come on. Daph.

696
00:34:08.580 --> 00:34:10.781
How the hell did
she know all that?

697
00:34:10.849 --> 00:34:13.282
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

698
00:34:13.351 --> 00:34:15.819
Ms. Downs? I'm Detective
Cho. this is Detective Hixon.

699
00:34:15.887 --> 00:34:18.599
If it's not too much trouble. we'd
like to ask you a few questions.

700
00:34:18.623 --> 00:34:20.857
About? Your former
boyfriend. Reed Koblenz.

701
00:34:20.926 --> 00:34:23.226
Reed? I haven't seen
him since I posted his bail.

702
00:34:23.294 --> 00:34:25.214
If you find him. tell him
he owes me two grand.

703
00:34:27.232 --> 00:34:28.631
Okay.

704
00:34:28.700 --> 00:34:31.434
If he attempts any
contact. please let us know.

705
00:34:36.642 --> 00:34:37.707
Koblenz?

706
00:34:44.750 --> 00:34:46.015
(EXCLAIMS)

707
00:34:47.919 --> 00:34:50.720
Pack everything
up. then disappear.

708
00:34:50.789 --> 00:34:53.149
This one is my insurance policy.

709
00:34:58.230 --> 00:35:00.350
DAPHNE: Remembering
when we used to be normal?

710
00:35:02.133 --> 00:35:04.053
You okay? Yeah. I'm fine.

711
00:35:04.302 --> 00:35:06.068
I just wanna be alone.

712
00:35:06.138 --> 00:35:08.771
I know I haven't always
been there for you.

713
00:35:10.508 --> 00:35:11.774
(SIGHS)

714
00:35:11.843 --> 00:35:13.409
but I'm here now.

715
00:35:18.317 --> 00:35:19.348
Did it happen again?

716
00:35:22.453 --> 00:35:23.987
I was with Lucas.

717
00:35:26.258 --> 00:35:29.025
And when I looked in his
eyes. I could read his thoughts.

718
00:35:30.963 --> 00:35:32.962
He's sleeping with Emily.

719
00:35:39.705 --> 00:35:40.815
That bitch.

720
00:35:40.839 --> 00:35:42.172
I know. right?

721
00:35:43.975 --> 00:35:46.042
And he said he loved me.

722
00:35:46.111 --> 00:35:47.844
(SNIFFLING) That
he would wait for me.

723
00:35:49.715 --> 00:35:52.048
Why would he say
it if it wasn't true?

724
00:35:53.818 --> 00:35:56.052
It's not fair! I
can't be a virgin

725
00:35:56.121 --> 00:35:57.487
and a freak.

726
00:35:59.558 --> 00:36:00.690
JJ: What's going on?

727
00:36:02.294 --> 00:36:04.127
Oh. Talking about
your new cool powers.

728
00:36:04.196 --> 00:36:06.262
Keep me updated on
the costume design.

729
00:36:06.331 --> 00:36:07.830
JJ. stop.

730
00:36:10.568 --> 00:36:13.014
We're a family. no
matter what happens to us.

731
00:36:13.038 --> 00:36:15.116
Or what doesn't happen to us.

732
00:36:15.140 --> 00:36:16.350
Nothing's gonna change that.

733
00:36:16.374 --> 00:36:17.614
You understand?

734
00:36:19.378 --> 00:36:21.678
Yeah.

735
00:36:21.746 --> 00:36:25.426
I think I liked us better when
we were just dysfunctional.

736
00:36:32.357 --> 00:36:33.535
Hey!

737
00:36:33.559 --> 00:36:34.657
Let her go.

738
00:36:34.726 --> 00:36:36.025
(GROANS IN FRUSTRATION)

739
00:36:37.161 --> 00:36:38.995
If I let her go

740
00:36:39.064 --> 00:36:41.309
she wouldn't make a very
good hostage now. would she?

741
00:36:41.333 --> 00:36:42.732
I'm warning you.

742
00:36:42.800 --> 00:36:44.960
You don't have a partner
here this time to stop me.

743
00:36:46.038 --> 00:36:47.570
Who says I ever did?

744
00:36:48.940 --> 00:36:50.980
You thought you
were the only one?

745
00:36:56.114 --> 00:36:57.214
(GROANS)

746
00:37:18.704 --> 00:37:20.303
(PANTING)

747
00:37:20.371 --> 00:37:23.306
Last time we met.
I didn't kill you.

748
00:37:23.375 --> 00:37:25.408
But then again. I shot
you from four feet away.

749
00:37:26.110 --> 00:37:27.711
Don't you know?

750
00:37:27.779 --> 00:37:29.646
You and me. we're not...

751
00:37:29.715 --> 00:37:31.047
(GUNSHOT)

752
00:37:37.322 --> 00:37:38.855
What are you doing here. Powell?

753
00:37:38.924 --> 00:37:40.323
Trying to be some sort of hero?

754
00:37:40.392 --> 00:37:41.791
I...

755
00:37:41.860 --> 00:37:45.300
Get out of here now. Before
you're answering questions from I.A.

756
00:38:03.281 --> 00:38:04.680
Hey.

757
00:38:04.749 --> 00:38:06.483
I'm home.

758
00:38:07.952 --> 00:38:09.118
Jim.

759
00:38:11.822 --> 00:38:13.322
We need to talk.

760
00:38:21.199 --> 00:38:25.034
You may have felt like
you couldn't keep up.

761
00:38:25.103 --> 00:38:28.405
But while I was racing
to be the perfect spouse.

762
00:38:28.473 --> 00:38:30.039
the perfect parent.

763
00:38:31.643 --> 00:38:33.176
you were it.

764
00:38:38.483 --> 00:38:41.284
You were extraordinary before
you could ever catch a bullet.

765
00:38:43.989 --> 00:38:47.690
Maybe it's taken something crazy
to make us thankful for what we have.

766
00:38:50.328 --> 00:38:51.661
Promise me.

767
00:38:54.098 --> 00:38:56.032
no more bullets. no
more crime fighting.

768
00:38:57.769 --> 00:39:00.970
Because in a way I feel
like I'm just getting you back.

769
00:39:02.774 --> 00:39:04.207
Okay.

770
00:39:04.275 --> 00:39:05.842
I promise.

771
00:39:09.447 --> 00:39:10.846
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

772
00:39:15.286 --> 00:39:16.953
TEACHER: All right.

773
00:39:17.021 --> 00:39:19.333
You have 20 minutes to solve the
equation I've written on the board.

774
00:39:19.357 --> 00:39:22.002
Solve for x. and make
sure you show all your work.

775
00:39:22.026 --> 00:39:23.959
Dude. You study for this?

776
00:39:24.028 --> 00:39:25.428
Why bother?

777
00:39:25.496 --> 00:39:27.096
TEACHER: You may begin now.

778
00:39:32.537 --> 00:39:34.069
(SIGHING)

779
00:40:06.438 --> 00:40:09.338
What are you doing. man?
Jeez! Just take a look and see.

780
00:40:10.608 --> 00:40:11.741
George.

781
00:40:13.110 --> 00:40:14.511
What did you do?

782
00:40:14.579 --> 00:40:16.045
You've got a new hobby now.

783
00:40:17.282 --> 00:40:19.682
Yeah. my brother knows a guy.

784
00:40:19.751 --> 00:40:21.150
You need Blu-ray. anything.

785
00:40:21.219 --> 00:40:22.663
So. you turned
your garage into...

786
00:40:22.687 --> 00:40:23.986
That's right.

787
00:40:24.055 --> 00:40:26.415
What every secret
crime fighter needs.

788
00:40:27.058 --> 00:40:28.098
A lair.

789
00:40:29.093 --> 00:40:30.213
With Wi-Fi.

790
00:40:31.229 --> 00:40:33.062
I have a lair?

791
00:40:33.131 --> 00:40:34.530
With Wi-Fi?

792
00:40:34.599 --> 00:40:35.932
Uh-huh.

793
00:40:37.068 --> 00:40:39.502
Huh?

794
00:40:39.570 --> 00:40:43.773
I know it's quite a story but you
asked us how we got here. so.

795
00:40:46.711 --> 00:40:48.210
Did I leave anything out?

796
00:40:48.279 --> 00:40:50.759
No. I think you hit
all the highlights.

797
00:40:51.883 --> 00:40:52.916
So?

798
00:40:55.053 --> 00:40:56.786
What do you think. Dr. Allen?

799
00:40:58.824 --> 00:41:00.389
I think

800
00:41:00.458 --> 00:41:03.726
we've got our
work cut out for us.

801
00:41:03.794 --> 00:41:06.996
Might I suggest we
start with twice a week?

802
00:41:07.999 --> 00:41:09.543
Sure. Sounds great.

803
00:41:09.567 --> 00:41:11.500
We want this to work.

804
00:41:11.569 --> 00:41:13.069
Not just for us

805
00:41:13.838 --> 00:41:15.338
but for our family.

806
00:41:21.012 --> 00:41:23.613
JIM: <i>The problems we face
may no longer be ordinary.</i>

807
00:41:26.685 --> 00:41:27.917
<i>But then again.</i>

808
00:41:30.421 --> 00:41:31.920
<i>neither are we.</i>

809
00:41:58.249 --> 00:41:59.515
(SIGHS)

810
00:42:00.651 --> 00:42:02.986
DR. KING: I see you
found Mr. Koblenz.

811
00:42:04.622 --> 00:42:06.942
Find out who knows about him.

812
00:42:07.525 --> 00:42:09.225
And then take care of it.
